snippet.textDisplay:
I spoke to my friend about Coronavirus last night, he's a chemistry PhD and senior demonstrator at a good university and said what we all suspect; that China's dealing with Coronavirus was very well-handled as Dr Aylward attests to here. The Chinese are of course required to take their government's advice and instruction seriously or face significant penalties, (a degree of control Boris Johnson can only dream of) their compliance coupled with their government's robust decontamination measures are suggestive of a good outcome.


The depressing part is this, having worked in construction and watched grown men emerge from stinking stalls only to pass the taps and go about sharing their faecal matter with the world, or to be forced to use a portable toilet with no way to clean your hands, to think of how many rolled up notes and straws are being shared snorting cocaine 24/7. These behaviours and conditions now take on huge significance at a time where I've never seen my peers so unhappy, so ignorant, so selfish.


Any comparison done with China (with respect to infection rates) must take into account that a far larger portion of the population in the UK won't comply with advice or will be ignorant of it,. Whenever I consider the banquet of approaching catastrophes, I don't have to think for long before finding incredible human stupidity.



It will be the NHS that will be the hero in the end after significant damage to population numbers, having saved the lives of so many ignorant, selfish arseholes who thought it would be better to allow the tories to break it up and feast on its corpse than to nurture and preserve what is still one of the greatest institutions ever to exist.


To all NHS staff: Thank you so much for putting your own lives at risk and thank you so much for what you do every day in the face of more cuts and poorer working conditions, and especially to the agency staff on minimum wage who won't even get paid for taking sick days.
